This lets you embed BaGet into your own custom ASP.NET Core application.

<details>
<summary>Embedding code example...</summary>

I added a sample application here: [`samples/BaGetWebApplication`](https://github.com/loic-sharma/BaGet/tree/loshar-refactor-di/samples/BaGetWebApplication)

Here's the interesting bit:

```cs
public class Startup
{
  public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
  {
    services.AddBaGetWebApplication(app =>
    {
      // Use SQLite as the database and store packages on the filesystem.
      app.AddSqliteDatabase();
      app.AddFileStorage();
    }
  }

  public void Configure(ApplicationBuilder app, IWebHostEnvironment env)
  {
    app.UseRouting();
    app.UseEndpoints(endpoints =>
    {
      var api = new BaGetApi();

      api.MapRoutes(endpoints);
    }
  }
}
```
</details>

This change removes BaGet's knowledge of the different database and storage providers, thereby allowing BaGet's dependency injection logic to be pushed down to the `BaGet.Hosting` and `BaGet.Core` projects. The app must now register its storage and database providers using the new `BaGetApplication` type.

