After migrating from _NuGet.Server_ to _BaGet_ ussing the [suggested script](https://loic-sharma.github.io/BaGet/tools/migrate/#migrate-from-nugetserver), we ended up with the _Versions_ section of each package in a more or less random order.

Digging up the code, I've found that the Versions views assumes the list is ordered following SemVer, and reverses it:

```tsx
  public render() {
    // Show the versions from greatest to smallest.
    // We clone the versions array to avoid modifying the props.
    // This assumes the versions are ordered by semver ascendingly.
    let versionsToRender = [...this.props.versions];
    versionsToRender.reverse();
    if (!this.state.showAll) {
      versionsToRender = versionsToRender.slice(0, Versions.defaultVisible);
    }
```

But the method `FindAsync` in `PackageService` does not enforce an order:

```csharp
        public async Task<IReadOnlyList<Package>> FindAsync(string id, bool includeUnlisted, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
        {
            var query = _context.Packages
                .Include(p => p.Dependencies)
                .Include(p => p.PackageTypes)
                .Include(p => p.TargetFrameworks)
                .Where(p => p.Id == id);

            if (!includeUnlisted)
            {
                query = query.Where(p => p.Listed);
            }

            return (await query.ToListAsync(cancellationToken)).AsReadOnly();
        }
```

So the packages end up ordered (indirectly) by `Key`. This happens to be the "correct" order, indirectly, if packages are published naturally during their lifetime, assuming each new version has a higher _SemVer_ than the previous.

But I think it would be better to enforce the assumed ordering in the service to avoid any ambiguity (like for example the one we got into after a migration). Not forcing an order could also break normal use cases: if someone publish a bugfix package for a previous (lower) major version, that version would be the first one shown in the _Versions_ section, breaking the ordering.

